1234–Female":"1234–Overleden","1239–1306":"1239–1306","1175–1235":"1175–1235","1178–Female":"1178–Overleden","1190":"1190","1230":"1230","1175":"1175","1206":"1206","1228":"1228","1239":"1239","1205":"1205","1226":"1226","1236":"1236","1235":"1235","1268":"1268","1234":"1234","1178":"1178","1277":"1277","1265":"1265","1232":"1232","1306":"1306","Lewes, Sussex, England":"Lewes, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stoke d'Abernon, Epsom, Surrey, England":"Stoke D'abernon, Surrey, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stoke D'Abernon, Surrey, England":"Stoke D'abernon, Surrey, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1206–1265":"1206–1265","1205–1236":"1205–1236","1232–1277":"1232–1277","1190–1268":"1190–1268","1226–Female":"1226–Deceased","1228–Male":"1228–Deceased","1230–Male":"1230–Deceased","1234–Female":"1234–Deceased","1239–1306":"1239–1306","1175–1235":"1175–1235","1178–Female":"1178–Deceased","1190":"1190","1230":"1230","1175":"1175","1206":"1206","1228":"1228","1239":"1239","1205":"1205","1226":"1226","1236":"1236","1235":"1235","1268":"1268","1234":"1234","1178":"1178","1277":"1277","1265":"1265","1232":"1232","1306":"1306","Lewes, Sussex, England":"Lewes, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Stoke d'Abernon, Epsom, Surrey, England":"Stoke D'abernon, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Stoke D'Abernon, Surrey, England":"Stoke D'abernon, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Maud d'Abernon was born in 1206, in Stoke D'abernon, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, her father, Roger d’Abernon, was 31 and her mother, Basilia de Odingsells, was 29. She had at least 3 sons and 2 daughters with Henry Sidney. She died in 1265, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1206–1265":"1206–1265","1205–1236":"1205–1236","1232–1277":"1232–1277","1190–1268":"1190–1268","1226–Female":"1226–Surnud","1228–Male":"1228–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1234–Female":"1234–Surnud","1239–1306":"1239–1306","1175–1235":"1175–1235","1178–Female":"1178–Surnud","1190":"1190","1230":"1230","1175":"1175","1206":"1206","1228":"1228","1239":"1239","1205":"1205","1226":"1226","1236":"1236","1235":"1235","1268":"1268","1234":"1234","1178":"1178","1277":"1277","1265":"1265","1232":"1232","1306":"1306","Lewes, Sussex, England":"Lewes, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stoke d'Abernon, Epsom, Surrey, England":"Stoke D'abernon, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stoke D'Abernon, Surrey, England":"Stoke D'abernon, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1206–1265":"1206–1265","1205–1236":"1205–1236","1232–1277":"1232–1277","1190–1268":"1190–1268","1226–Female":"1226–Kuollut","1228–Male":"1228–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1234–Female":"1234–Kuollut","1239–1306":"1239–1306","117